author: Matt Zenitz | mzenitz@al.com
title: Alabama freshman receives national honor
text:
Comments 
Alabama freshman cornerback Minkah Fitzpatrick was named Walter Camp National Defensive Player of the Week Sunday. 
Fitzpatrick became the first player in Tide history to return two interceptions for touchdowns in the same game during Alabama's 41-23 win over Texas A&M on Saturday. 
Fitzpatrick finished with two tackles and the two pick-sixes. 
The first pick-six produced the Tide's first points midway through the first quarter, an interception of Aggies quarterback Kyle Allen that Fitzpatrick returned 33 yards for a touchdown. 
The second essentially sealed Alabama's win with around five minutes left in the fourth quarter. 
Fitzpatrick intercepted Allen again before running 55 yards for a score that pushed the Tide's lead to 41-23. 
RELATED: Inside Minkah Fitzpatrick's rise from 'peanut butter room' to one of Alabama's top young players 
In seven games, Fitzpatrick is tied for fifth on the Tide with 24 tackles, has three stops for a loss, two sacks, the two pick-sixes, a team-high six pass breakups among non-defensive linemen and a blocked punt that he recovered and returned for a touchdown.
